00:00:47.920 --> 00:00:54.920
 get to the biology of reproduction and aging because it happened at the University of Oregon.

00:00:54.920 --> 00:01:04.740
 These people were less dogmatic than the ones in nerve biology. And some of the most interesting

00:01:04.740 --> 00:01:15.000
 work at the University was being done in biochemistry and so most of my course work was in biochemistry

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:23.360
 and endocrinology and the biology of progesterone, estrogen and tissue respiration was the center

00:01:23.360 --> 00:01:39.400
 of my thesis and that led to interest in organismic respiration as controlled by thyroid and its

00:01:39.400 --> 00:01:46.400
 interactions with progesterone and estrogen. And by chance, before I had begun studying

00:01:46.400 --> 00:02:03.160
 at the University in 1968, I had visited Russia to talk to a biologist there who was studying

00:02:09.100 --> 00:02:16.100
 the interactions of magnetic fields and nervous system and the endocrine system and because

00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:23.800
 of my contact with the Russian literature, I ran into Buteko's work right around that

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:31.300
 same time and I respected what he was doing because he was one of the few people in the

00:02:33.720 --> 00:02:40.720
 world that really took the physiology of carbon dioxide seriously. So many American biologists

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:51.960
 and physicians in particular think of it as a waste material rather than as a crucial

00:02:51.960 --> 00:02:58.960
 biochemical. In the early 1940s, someone demonstrated that many organisms can live and reproduce

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:08.520
 even without oxygen but they could find no cell or organism that could live and reproduce

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:18.380
 in the absence of carbon dioxide. So biologically, it's in a way much more fundamental than oxygen

00:03:22.560 --> 00:03:33.560
 and I didn't study much of Buteko after that. I was just aware that he was one of the few

00:03:33.560 --> 00:03:40.560
 people who had worked out the complex biochemical effects of carbon dioxide but I would periodically

00:03:40.560 --> 00:03:49.600
 check what the Russians were doing in relation to carbon dioxide physiology. There were a

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:56.600
 few others besides Buteko, but it was really central to many of the things that I worked

00:03:56.600 --> 00:04:06.360
 on because progesterone and carbon dioxide, for example, both have an energizing and calming

00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:16.560
 effect on all cells, everything from the brain to the secretory and hormonal effects of carbon

00:04:16.560 --> 00:04:23.560
 dioxide, respiratory and hormonal tissues. My interest was not particularly in relation

00:04:23.560 --> 00:04:42.560
 to asthma, but Buteko noticed many other effects of carbon dioxide when he was working with

00:04:44.840 --> 00:04:51.840
 people treating asthma as the focus. He noticed that some of the patients recovered from other

00:04:51.840 --> 00:05:01.300
 degenerative terminal diseases and those have been where I've spent most of my effort thinking

00:05:01.300 --> 00:05:10.600
 about the role of carbon dioxide in all of the inflammatory and degenerative diseases

00:05:11.280 --> 00:05:18.280
 and how it works synergistically with progesterone and protectively against the toxic effects

00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:26.780
 of estrogen and other excitatory molecules. It turns out that all of the degenerative

00:05:26.780 --> 00:05:35.160
 diseases are centered on an excess of inflammatory processes which de-energize the cells and

00:05:38.840 --> 00:05:45.840
 shift the metabolism away from the production of carbon dioxide with a dominant tendency

00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:53.800
 towards producing lactic acid in excess that can't be consumed and converted to carbon dioxide.

00:05:53.800 --> 00:06:03.240
 Well, that's a great introduction, Ray. As usual, wonderfully complex. Now, as I said

